By concentrating all the wealth with one individual, we’re not fully realizing our collective potential. Blaming billionaires does not solve this. We created the current system. We voted for the representatives that wrote these laws and enabled this environment. We can change it.
With that kind of financial ability they can also become entrepreneurs and founders, build new products and create further value, more jobs, and greater wealth.

If workers were proportionately compensated compared to a company’s valuation, we would have tens of thousands of multi-millionaires from just one successful company. Many of these workers could have the potential for even greater innovation.

However, none of that is possible without worker contributions, whether that’s in ideas, patents, process improvements, or time worked at a job. It’s also not possible without building on the existing advancements and infrastructure that others were responsible for.
Creating a successful company from the ground up is an accomplishment. Getting technologically innovative products and services to market at scale in regulated markets should be recognized.

There is a difference between equating a company’s collective accomplishments and financial value, made possible by hundreds or thousands of workers vs. recognizing the ability to lead that effort as a founder, angel investor, or CEO.
If you or I had a 100 billion dollars, would we want to give it to the US government to use at their discretion or invest it into projects that we believe are better use of our wealth?
THREAD: This is not about Elon Musk or any individual billionaire. Anyone that can take advantage of the current tax system to preserve wealth, will do so.
